# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hamiltonian-monte-carlo
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] In thermodynamics, the principle of **detailed balance** says that every process of energy transfer in one direction must also allow energy transfer in the opposite direction, and in equilibrium, the flux in both directions must be equal.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For example, the principle can be used in kinetic systems which are decomposed into elementary processes (collisions, or steps, or elementary reactions).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] It states that at equilibrium, each elementary process is in equilibrium with its reverse process.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The principle of detailed balance was explicitly introduced for collisions by Ludwig Boltzmann.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] In 1872, he proved his H-theorem using this principle.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The arguments in favor of this property are founded upon microscopic reversibility.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Five years before Boltzmann, James Clerk Maxwell used the principle of detailed balance for gas kinetics with the reference to the principle of sufficient reason.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] He compared the idea of detailed balance with other types of balancing (like cyclic balance) and found that "Now it is impossible to assign a reason" why detailed balance should be rejected (p.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] In 1901, Rudolf Wegscheider introduced the principle of detailed balance for chemical kinetics.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] In particular, he demonstrated that the irreversible cycles ${\ce {A1->A2->\cdots ->A_{\mathit {n}}->A1}}$ are impossible and found explicitly the relations between kinetic constants that follow from the principle of detailed balance.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] In 1931, Lars Onsager used these relations in his works, for which he was awarded the 1968 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The principle of detailed balance has been used in Markov chain Monte Carlo methods since their invention in 1953.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] In particular, in the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm and in its important particular case, Gibbs sampling, it is used as a simple and reliable condition to provide the desirable equilibrium state.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Now, the principle of detailed balance is a standard part of the university courses in statistical mechanics, physical chemistry, chemical and physical kinetics.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The microscopic "reversing of time" turns at the kinetic level into the "reversing of arrows": the elementary processes transform into their reverse processes.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The equilibrium ensemble should be invariant with respect to this transformation because of microreversibility and the uniqueness of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] This leads us immediately to the concept of detailed balance: each process is equilibrated by its reverse process.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The macroscopic elementary processes are microscopically distinguishable.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] That is, they represent disjoint sets of microscopic events.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Any of these assumptions may be violated.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For example, Boltzmann's collision can be represented as ${\ce {A_{\mathit {v}}+A_{\mathit {w}}->A_{\mathit {v'}}+A_{\mathit {w'}}}}$ , where ${\ce {A}}_{v}$ is a particle with velocity *v*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Therefore, the collision is transformed into the reverse collision by the *PT* transformation, where *P* is the space inversion and *T* is the time reversal.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Detailed balance for Boltzmann's equation requires *PT*-invariance of collisions' dynamics, not just *T*-invariance.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For this purpose, we need to apply additionally the space reversal *P*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Therefore, for the detailed balance in Boltzmann's equation not *T*-invariance but *PT*-invariance is needed.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Equilibrium may be not *T*- or *PT*-invariant even if the laws of motion are invariant.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] This non-invariance may be caused by the spontaneous symmetry breaking.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] There exist *nonreciprocal media* (for example, some bi-isotropic materials) without *T* and *PT* invariance.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] If different macroscopic processes are sampled from the same elementary microscopic events then macroscopic detailed balance may be violated even when microscopic detailed balance holds.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Now, after almost 150 years of development, the scope of validity and the violations of detailed balance in kinetics seem to be clear.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] *P**ij* = *P*(*X**t* = *j* | *X**t* − 1 = *i*), and π*i* and π*j* are the equilibrium probabilities of being in states *i* and *j*, respectively.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] When Pr(*X**t*−1 = *i*) = π*i* for all *i*, this is equivalent to the joint probability matrix, Pr(*X**t*−1 = *i*, *X**t* = *j*) being symmetric in *i* and *j*; or symmetric in *t* − 1 and *t*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Transition matrices that are symmetric (*P**ij* = *P**ji* or *P*(*s*′, *s*) = *P*(*s*, *s*′)) always have detailed balance.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] In these cases, a uniform distribution over the states is an equilibrium distribution.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Reversibility is equivalent to Kolmogorov's criterion: the product of transition rates over any closed loop of states is the same in both directions.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For example, it implies that, for all *a*, *b* and *c*, $P(a,b)P(b,c)P(c,a)=P(a,c)P(c,b)P(b,a)\,.$ For example, if we have a Markov chain with three states such that only these transitions are possible: $A\to B,B\to C,C\to A,B\to A$ , then they violate Kolmogorov's criterion.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For continuous systems with detailed balance, it may be possible to continuously transform the coordinates until the equilibrium distribution is uniform, with a transition kernel which then is symmetric.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] In the case of discrete states, it may be possible to achieve something similar by breaking the Markov states into appropriately-sized degenerate sub-states.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For a Markov transition matrix and a stationary distribution, the detailed balance equations may not be valid.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] However, it can be shown that a unique Markov transition matrix exists which is closest according to the stationary distribution and a given norm.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The closest Matrix can be computed by solving a quadratic-convex optimization problem.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For many systems of physical and chemical kinetics, detailed balance provides *sufficient conditions* for the strict increase of entropy in isolated systems.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For example, the famous Boltzmann H-theorem states that, according to the Boltzmann equation, the principle of detailed balance implies positivity of entropy production.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The Boltzmann formula (1872) for entropy production in rarefied gas kinetics with detailed balance served as a prototype of many similar formulas for dissipation in mass action kinetics and generalized mass action kinetics with detailed balance.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Nevertheless, the principle of detailed balance is not necessary for entropy growth.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For example, in the linear irreversible cycle ${\ce {A1 -> A2 -> A3 -> A1}}$ , entropy production is positive but the principle of detailed balance does not hold.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Thus, the principle of detailed balance is a sufficient but not necessary condition for entropy increase in Boltzmann kinetics.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] These relations between the principle of detailed balance and the second law of thermodynamics were clarified in 1887 when Hendrik Lorentz objected to the Boltzmann H-theorem for polyatomic gases.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Lorentz stated that the principle of detailed balance is not applicable to collisions of polyatomic molecules.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Boltzmann immediately invented a new, more general condition sufficient for entropy growth.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Boltzmann's condition holds for all Markov processes, irrespective of time-reversibility.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Later, entropy increase was proved for all Markov processes by a direct method.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] These theorems may be considered as simplifications of the Boltzmann result.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Later, this condition was referred to as the "cyclic balance" condition (because it holds for irreversible cycles) or the "semi-detailed balance" or the "complex balance".
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] In 1981, Carlo Cercignani and Maria Lampis proved that the Lorentz arguments were wrong and the principle of detailed balance is valid for polyatomic molecules.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Nevertheless, the extended semi-detailed balance conditions invented by Boltzmann in this discussion remain the remarkable generalization of the detailed balance.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Here, the reverse reactions with positive constants are included in the list separately.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] We need this separation of direct and reverse reactions to apply later the general formalism to the systems with some irreversible reactions.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The system of stoichiometric equations of elementary reactions is the *reaction mechanism*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The *stoichiometric vector* $\gamma _{r}$ is the *r*th row of ${\boldsymbol {\Gamma }}$ with coordinates $\gamma _{ri}=\beta _{ri}-\alpha _{ri}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] According to the *generalized mass action law*, the reaction rate for an elementary reaction is $w_{r}=k_{r}\prod _{i=1}^{n}a_{i}^{\alpha _{ri}}\,,$ where $a_{i}\geq 0$ is the activity (the "effective concentration") of $A_{i}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The reaction mechanism includes reactions with the reaction rate constants $k_{r}>0$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For a reversible reaction, $K_{r}=k_{r}^{+}/k_{r}^{-}$ is the equilibrium constant.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The principle of detailed balance for the generalized mass action law is: For given values $k_{r}$ there exists a positive equilibrium $a_{i}^{\rm {eq}}>0$ that satisfies detailed balance, that is, $w_{r}^{+}=w_{r}^{-}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The following classical result gives the necessary and sufficient conditions for the existence of a positive equilibrium $a_{i}^{\rm {eq}}>0$ with detailed balance (see, for example, the textbook).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] In particular, for any cycle in the monomolecular (linear) reactions the product of the reaction rate constants in the clockwise direction is equal to the product of the reaction rate constants in the counterclockwise direction.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The same condition is valid for the reversible Markov processes (it is equivalent to the "no net flow" condition).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The computational aspect of the Wegscheider conditions was studied by D.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The Wegscheider conditions demonstrate that whereas the principle of detailed balance states a local property of equilibrium, it implies the relations between the kinetic constants that are valid for all states far from equilibrium.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] This is possible because a kinetic law is known and relations between the rates of the elementary processes at equilibrium can be transformed into relations between kinetic constants which are used globally.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For the Wegscheider conditions this kinetic law is the law of mass action (or the generalized law of mass action).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] To describe dynamics of the systems that obey the generalized mass action law, one has to represent the activities as functions of the concentrations *cj* and temperature.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The chemical potential can be represented as a function of *c* and *T*, where *c* is the vector of concentrations with components *cj*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For the ideal systems, $\mu _{i}=RT\ln c_{i}+\mu _{i}^{\ominus }$ and $a_{j}=c_{j}$ : the activity is the concentration and the generalized mass action law is the usual law of mass action.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Consider a system in isothermal (*T*=const) isochoric (the volume *V*=const) condition.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For these conditions, the Helmholtz free energy ⁠ $F(T,V,N)$ ⁠ measures the "useful" work obtainable from a system.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] It is a functions of the temperature *T*, the volume *V* and the amounts of chemical components *Nj* (usually measured in moles), *N* is the vector with components *Nj*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The chemical potential is a partial derivative: $\mu _{i}=\partial F(T,V,N)/\partial N_{i}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Let the principle of detailed balance be valid.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] These symmetry relations, $L_{ij}=L_{ji}$ , are exactly the Onsager reciprocal relations.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The coefficient matrix L is non-positive.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] It is negative on the linear span of the stoichiometric vectors $\gamma _{r}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] So, the Onsager relations follow from the principle of detailed balance in the linear approximation near equilibrium.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] There need not be a (global) detailed balance as reservoirs can have different temperatures, chemical potentials, etc.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] In mathematical terms, the condition of local detailed balance assures that the logarithmic ratio of the probability of a trajectory to the probability of the time-reversed trajectory equals the entropy flux per *k*B to the system environment.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] It is important here that the environment consists of mutually separated thermodynamic equilibrium baths.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] In particular, local detailed balance allows identification of currents and entropy flows, and is directly related to the so-called fluctuation theorems for entropy fluxes.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] As shown in a series of publications, local detailed balance implies detailed, integrated, local, steady-state or transient fluctuation theorems for the entropy flux satisfying a Gallavotti–Cohen-like symmetry.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Discussions and derivations of local detailed balance are found in.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Not all models that are commonly used in nonequilibrium statistical mechanics satisfy local detailed balance, which makes it less evident how to associate heat and entropy fluxes to the proposed dynamics.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] To formulate the principle of semi-detailed balance, it is convenient to count the direct and inverse elementary reactions separately.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Let Y be the set of all these vectors $\alpha _{r},\beta _{r}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] $r\in R_{\nu }^{+}$ if and only if $\nu$ is the vector of the input stoichiometric coefficients $\alpha _{r}$ for the *r*th elementary reaction; $r\in R_{\nu }^{-}$ if and only if $\nu$ is the vector of the output stoichiometric coefficients $\beta _{r}$ for the *r*th elementary reaction.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For the Markov kinetics the semi-detailed balance condition is just the elementary balance equation and holds for any steady state.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For the nonlinear mass action law it is, in general, sufficient but not necessary condition for stationarity.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The semi-detailed balance condition is weaker than the detailed balance one: if the principle of detailed balance holds then the condition of semi-detailed balance also holds.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Boltzmann introduced the semi-detailed balance condition for collisions in 1887 and proved that it guaranties the positivity of the entropy production.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For chemical kinetics, this condition (as the *complex balance* condition) was introduced by Horn and Jackson in 1972.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The microscopic backgrounds for the semi-detailed balance were found in the Markov microkinetics of the intermediate compounds that are present in small amounts and whose concentrations are in quasiequilibrium with the main components.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Under these microscopic assumptions, the semi-detailed balance condition is just the balance equation for the Markov microkinetics according to the **Michaelis–Menten–Stueckelberg theorem**.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The exponential term is called the *Boltzmann factor* and the multiplier $\varphi _{r}\geq 0$ is the kinetic factor.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For $\lambda =1$ it is just the sum of the reaction rates.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The function $\theta (\lambda )$ is convex because $\theta ''(\lambda )\geq 0$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Direct calculation gives that according to the kinetic equations ${\frac {dF}{dt}}=-VRT\left.{\frac {d\theta (\lambda )}{d\lambda }}\right|_{\lambda =1}$ This is *the general dissipation formula for the generalized mass action law*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The semi-detailed balance condition can be transformed into identity $\theta (0)\equiv \theta (1)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Therefore, for the systems with semi-detailed balance ${dF}/{dt}\leq 0$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] The **cone theorem** states that for the given reaction mechanism and given positive equilibrium, the velocity (*dN/dt*) at a state *N* for a system with complex balance belongs to the cone $\mathbf {Q} _{\rm {DB}}(N)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] That is, there exists a system with detailed balance, the same reaction mechanism, the same positive equilibrium, that gives the same velocity at state *N*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] According to cone theorem, for a given state *N*, the set of velocities of the semidetailed balance systems coincides with the set of velocities of the detailed balance systems if their reaction mechanisms and equilibria coincide.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] Detailed balance states that in equilibrium each elementary process is equilibrated by its reverse process and requires reversibility of all elementary processes.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For many real physico-chemical complex systems (e.g. homogeneous combustion, heterogeneous catalytic oxidation, most enzyme reactions etc.), detailed mechanisms include both reversible and irreversible reactions.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] If one represents irreversible reactions as limits of reversible steps, then it becomes obvious that not all reaction mechanisms with irreversible reactions can be obtained as limits of systems or reversible reactions with detailed balance.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/detailed-balance] For example, the irreversible cycle ${\ce {A1 -> A2 -> A3 -> A1}}$ cannot be obtained as such a limit but the reaction mechanism ${\ce {A1 -> A2 -> A3 <- A1}}$ can.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] In physics, **Hamiltonian mechanics** is a reformulation of Lagrangian mechanics that emerged in 1833.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Introduced by Sir William Rowan Hamilton, Hamiltonian mechanics replaces (generalized) velocities ${\dot {q}}^{i}$ used in Lagrangian mechanics with (generalized) *momenta*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Both theories provide interpretations of classical mechanics and describe the same physical phenomena.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hamiltonian mechanics has a close relationship with geometry (notably, symplectic geometry and Poisson structures) and serves as a link between classical and quantum mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] (Also *generalized momenta*, *conjugate momenta*, and *canonical momenta*).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Legendre transform of ${\mathcal {L}}$ turns $E_{\mathcal {L}}$ into a function ${\mathcal {H}}({\boldsymbol {p}},{\boldsymbol {q}},t)$ known as the **Hamiltonian**.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The ( $2n$ -dimensional) pair $({\boldsymbol {p}},{\boldsymbol {q}})$ is called *phase space coordinates*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] By rearranging the equation ${\boldsymbol {p}}=\partial {\mathcal {L}}/\partial {\dot {\boldsymbol {q}}}$ , we can write ${\dot {\boldsymbol {q}}}$ in terms of ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ and ${\boldsymbol {p}}$ as ${\dot {\boldsymbol {q}}}({\boldsymbol {q}},{\boldsymbol {p}})$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] So **1** becomes an equation in two variables: ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ and ${\boldsymbol {p}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] A path ${\boldsymbol {q}}\in {\mathcal {P}}(a,b,{\boldsymbol {x}}_{a},{\boldsymbol {x}}_{b})$ is a stationary point of ${\mathcal {S}}$ (and hence is an equation of motion) if and only if the path $({\boldsymbol {p}}(t),{\boldsymbol {q}}(t))$ in phase space coordinates obeys the Hamilton equations.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] A simple interpretation of Hamiltonian mechanics comes from its application on a one-dimensional system consisting of one nonrelativistic particle of mass m.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The value $H(p,q)$ of the Hamiltonian is the total energy of the system, in this case the sum of kinetic and potential energy, traditionally denoted T and V, respectively.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Here p is the momentum mv and q is the space coordinate.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Then ${\mathcal {H}}=T+V,\qquad T={\frac {p^{2}}{2m}},\qquad V=V(q)$ T is a function of p alone, while V is a function of q alone (i.e., T and V are scleronomic).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] In this example, the time derivative of q is the velocity, and so the first Hamilton equation means that the particle's velocity equals the derivative of its kinetic energy with respect to its momentum.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The time derivative of the momentum p equals the *Newtonian force*, and so the second Hamilton equation means that the force equals the negative gradient of potential energy.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] A spherical pendulum consists of a mass *m* moving without friction on the surface of a sphere.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The only forces acting on the mass are the reaction from the sphere and gravity.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Spherical coordinates are used to describe the position of the mass in terms of (*r*, *θ*, *φ*), where *r* is fixed, *r* = *ℓ*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] That is a consequence of the rotational symmetry of the system around the vertical axis.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Being absent from the Hamiltonian, azimuth $\varphi$ is a cyclic coordinate, which implies conservation of its conjugate momentum.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hamilton's equations can be derived by a calculation with the Lagrangian ⁠ ${\mathcal {L}}$ ⁠, generalized positions qi, and generalized velocities ⋅*q**i*, where ⁠ $i=1,\ldots ,n$ ⁠.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Here we work off-shell, meaning ⁠ $q^{i}$ ⁠, ⁠ ${\dot {q}}^{i}$ ⁠, ⁠ t ⁠ are independent coordinates in phase space, not constrained to follow any equations of motion (in particular, ${\dot {q}}^{i}$ is not a derivative of ⁠ $q^{i}$ ⁠).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] In the case of time-independent ${\mathcal {H}}$ and ⁠ ${\mathcal {L}}$ ⁠, i.e. ⁠ $\partial {\mathcal {H}}/\partial t=-\partial {\mathcal {L}}/\partial t=0$ ⁠, Hamilton's equations consist of 2*n* first-order differential equations, while Lagrange's equations consist of n second-order equations.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hamilton's equations usually do not reduce the difficulty of finding explicit solutions, but important theoretical results can be derived from them, because coordinates and momenta are independent variables with nearly symmetric roles.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] This effectively reduces the problem from n coordinates to (*n* − 1) coordinates: this is the basis of symplectic reduction in geometry.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] In the Lagrangian framework, the conservation of momentum also follows immediately, however all the generalized velocities ${\dot {q}}_{i}$ still occur in the Lagrangian, and a system of equations in n coordinates still has to be solved.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Lagrangian and Hamiltonian approaches provide the groundwork for deeper results in classical mechanics, and suggest analogous formulations in quantum mechanics: the path integral formulation and the Schrödinger equation.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] where T is the kinetic energy and V is the potential energy.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Using this relation can be simpler than first calculating the Lagrangian, and then deriving the Hamiltonian from the Lagrangian.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] However, the relation is not true for all systems.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] where t is time, n is the number of degrees of freedom of the system, and each $c_{ij}({\boldsymbol {q}})$ is an arbitrary scalar function of ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] In words, this means that the relation ${\mathcal {H}}=T+V$ holds true if T does not contain time as an explicit variable (it is scleronomic), V does not contain generalised velocity as an explicit variable, and each term of T is quadratic in generalised velocity.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Preliminary to this proof, it is important to address an ambiguity in the related mathematical notation.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] In this case, the right hand side always evaluates to 0.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] To perform a change of variables inside of a partial derivative, the multivariable chain rule should be used.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hence, to avoid ambiguity, the function arguments of any term inside of a partial derivative should be stated.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Additionally, this proof uses the notation $f(a,b,c)=f(a,b)$ to imply that ${\frac {\partial f(a,b,c)}{\partial c}}=0$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] where each $c_{ij}({\boldsymbol {q}})$ is an arbitrary scalar function of ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] This simplification is a result of Euler's homogeneous function theorem.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] For a system of point masses, the requirement for T to be quadratic in generalised velocity is always satisfied for the case where $T({\boldsymbol {q}},{\boldsymbol {\dot {q}}},t)=T({\boldsymbol {q}},{\boldsymbol {\dot {q}}})$ , which is a requirement for ${\mathcal {H}}=T+V$ anyway.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Consider the kinetic energy for a system of N point masses.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] If the conditions for ${\mathcal {H}}=T+V$ are satisfied, then conservation of the Hamiltonian implies conservation of energy.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] This requires the additional condition that V does not contain time as an explicit variable.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Regarding extensions to the Euler-Lagrange formulation which use dissipation functions (See *Lagrangian mechanics § Extensions to include non-conservative forces*), e.g. the Rayleigh dissipation function, energy is not conserved when a dissipation function has effect.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] It is possible to explain the link between this and the former requirements by relating the extended and conventional Euler-Lagrange equations: grouping the extended terms into the potential function produces a velocity dependent potential.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hence, the requirements are not satisfied when a dissipation function has effect.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] A sufficient illustration of Hamiltonian mechanics is given by the Hamiltonian of a charged particle in an electromagnetic field.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] This Lagrangian, combined with Euler–Lagrange equation, produces the Lorentz force law $m{\ddot {\mathbf {x} }}=q\mathbf {E} +q{\dot {\mathbf {x} }}\times \mathbf {B} \,,$ and is called minimal coupling.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] This equation is used frequently in quantum mechanics.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Under gauge transformation: $\mathbf {A} \rightarrow \mathbf {A} +\nabla f\,,\quad \varphi \rightarrow \varphi -{\dot {f}}\,,$ where *f*(**r**, *t*) is any scalar function of space and time.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] In quantum mechanics, the wave function will also undergo a local U(1) group transformation during the Gauge Transformation, which implies that all physical results must be invariant under local U(1) transformations.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] As a closed nondegenerate symplectic 2-form *ω*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Due to the bilinearity and non-degeneracy of ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, and the fact that ⁠ $\dim T_{x}M=\dim T_{x}^{*}M$ ⁠, the mapping $\xi \to \omega _{\xi }$ is indeed a linear isomorphism.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] This isomorphism is *natural* in that it does not change with change of coordinates on $M.$ Repeating over all ⁠ $x\in M$ ⁠, we end up with an isomorphism $J^{-1}:{\text{Vect}}(M)\to \Omega ^{1}(M)$ between the infinite-dimensional space of smooth vector fields and that of smooth 1-forms.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] (In algebraic terms, one would say that the $C^{\infty }(M,\mathbb {R} )$ -modules ${\text{Vect}}(M)$ and $\Omega ^{1}(M)$ are isomorphic).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The respective differential equation on M ${\dot {x}}=J(dH)(x)$ is called *Hamilton's equation*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Here $x=x(t)$ and $J(dH)(x)\in T_{x}M$ is the (time-dependent) value of the vector field $J(dH)$ at ⁠ $x\in M$ ⁠.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] A Hamiltonian system may be understood as a fiber bundle E over time R, with the fiber Et being the position space at time *t* ∈ *R*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The correspondence between Lagrangian and Hamiltonian mechanics is achieved with the tautological one-form.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Any smooth real-valued function H on a symplectic manifold can be used to define a Hamiltonian system.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The function H is known as "the Hamiltonian" or "the energy function." The symplectic manifold is then called the phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Hamiltonian induces a special vector field on the symplectic manifold, known as the Hamiltonian vector field.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Hamiltonian vector field induces a Hamiltonian flow on the manifold.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] This is a one-parameter family of transformations of the manifold (the parameter of the curves is commonly called "the time"); in other words, an isotopy of symplectomorphisms, starting with the identity.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] By Liouville's theorem, each symplectomorphism preserves the volume form on the phase space.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The collection of symplectomorphisms induced by the Hamiltonian flow is commonly called "the Hamiltonian mechanics" of the Hamiltonian system.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The symplectic structure induces a Poisson bracket.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Poisson bracket gives the space of functions on the manifold the structure of a Lie algebra.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] If F and G are smooth functions on M then the smooth function *ω*(*J*(*dF*), *J*(*dG*)) is properly defined; it is called a *Poisson bracket* of functions F and G and is denoted {*F*, *G*}.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] 5. non-degeneracy: if the point x on M is not critical for F then a smooth function G exists such that ⁠ $\{F,G\}(x)\neq 0$ ⁠.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Every smooth function G over the symplectic manifold generates a one-parameter family of symplectomorphisms and if {*G*, *H*} = 0, then G is conserved and the symplectomorphisms are symmetry transformations.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] A Hamiltonian may have multiple conserved quantities *G**i*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] If the symplectic manifold has dimension 2*n* and there are n functionally independent conserved quantities Gi which are in involution (i.e., {*G**i*, *G**j*} = 0), then the Hamiltonian is Liouville integrable.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Liouville–Arnold theorem says that, locally, any Liouville integrable Hamiltonian can be transformed via a symplectomorphism into a new Hamiltonian with the conserved quantities Gi as coordinates; the new coordinates are called *action–angle coordinates*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The transformed Hamiltonian depends only on the *G**i*, and hence the equations of motion have the simple form ${\dot {G}}_{i}=0\quad ,\quad {\dot {\varphi }}_{i}=F_{i}(G)$ for some function F.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] There is an entire field focusing on small deviations from integrable systems governed by the KAM theorem.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The integrability of Hamiltonian vector fields is an open question.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] In general, Hamiltonian systems are chaotic; concepts of measure, completeness, integrability and stability are poorly defined.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] This Hamiltonian consists entirely of the kinetic term.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] If one considers a Riemannian manifold or a pseudo-Riemannian manifold, the Riemannian metric induces a linear isomorphism between the tangent and cotangent bundles.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Using this isomorphism, one can define a cometric.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] (In coordinates, the matrix defining the cometric is the inverse of the matrix defining the metric.) The solutions to the Hamilton–Jacobi equations for this Hamiltonian are then the same as the geodesics on the manifold.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] In particular, the Hamiltonian flow in this case is the same thing as the geodesic flow.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The existence of such solutions, and the completeness of the set of solutions, are discussed in detail in the article on geodesics.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] See also *Geodesics as Hamiltonian flows*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] When the cometric is degenerate, then it is not invertible.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] In this case, one does not have a Riemannian manifold, as one does not have a metric.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] In the case where the cometric is degenerate at every point q of the configuration space manifold Q, so that the rank of the cometric is less than the dimension of the manifold Q, one has a sub-Riemannian manifold.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Hamiltonian in this case is known as a **sub-Riemannian Hamiltonian**.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Every such Hamiltonian uniquely determines the cometric, and vice versa.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] This implies that every sub-Riemannian manifold is uniquely determined by its sub-Riemannian Hamiltonian, and that the converse is true: every sub-Riemannian manifold has a unique sub-Riemannian Hamiltonian.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The existence of sub-Riemannian geodesics is given by the Chow–Rashevskii theorem.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] The continuous, real-valued Heisenberg group provides a simple example of a sub-Riemannian manifold.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hamiltonian systems can be generalized in various ways.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Instead of simply looking at the algebra of smooth functions over a symplectic manifold, Hamiltonian mechanics can be formulated on general commutative unital real Poisson algebras.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] A state is a continuous linear functional on the Poisson algebra (equipped with some suitable topology) such that for any element A of the algebra, *A*2 maps to a nonnegative real number.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] A further generalization is given by Nambu dynamics.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hamilton's equations above work well for classical mechanics, but not for quantum mechanics, since the differential equations discussed assume that one can specify the exact position and momentum of the particle simultaneously at any point in time.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] However, the equations can be further generalized to then be extended to apply to quantum mechanics as well as to classical mechanics, through the deformation of the Poisson algebra over p and q to the algebra of Moyal brackets.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Specifically, the more general form of the Hamilton's equation reads ${\frac {\mathrm {d} f}{\mathrm {d} t}}=\left\{f,{\mathcal {H}}\right\}+{\frac {\partial f}{\partial t}},$ where f is some function of p and q, and H is the Hamiltonian.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] To find out the rules for evaluating a Poisson bracket without resorting to differential equations, see *Lie algebra*; a Poisson bracket is the name for the Lie bracket in a Poisson algebra.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] These Poisson brackets can then be extended to Moyal brackets comporting to an inequivalent Lie algebra, as proven by Hilbrand J.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] Groenewold, and thereby describe quantum mechanical diffusion in phase space (See *Phase space formulation* and *Wigner–Weyl transform*).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-mechanics] This more algebraic approach not only permits ultimately extending probability distributions in phase space to Wigner quasi-probability distributions, but, at the mere Poisson bracket classical setting, also provides more power in helping analyze the relevant conserved quantities in a system.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The **Hamiltonian Monte Carlo** algorithm (originally known as **hybrid Monte Carlo**) is a Markov chain Monte Carlo method for obtaining a sequence of random samples whose distribution converges to a target probability distribution that is difficult to sample directly.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] This sequence can be used to estimate integrals of the target distribution, such as expected values and moments.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Hamiltonian Monte Carlo corresponds to an instance of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, with a Hamiltonian dynamics evolution simulated using a time-reversible and volume-preserving numerical integrator (typically the leapfrog integrator) to propose a move to a new point in the state space.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The reduced correlation means fewer Markov chain samples are needed to approximate integrals with respect to the target probability distribution for a given Monte Carlo error.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The algorithm was originally proposed by Simon Duane, Anthony Kennedy, Brian Pendleton and Duncan Roweth in 1987 for calculations in lattice quantum chromodynamics.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Neal showed how the method could be used for a broader class of statistical problems, in particular artificial neural networks.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] But the burden of having to provide the algorithm with gradients of the model graph delayed its wider adoption in statistics and other quantitative disciplines, until in the mid-2010s the developers of Stan implemented HMC in combination with automatic differentiation.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Suppose the target distribution to sample is $f(\mathbf {x} )$ for $\mathbf {x} \in \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ ( $d\geq 1$ ) and a chain of samples $\mathbf {X} _{0},\mathbf {X} _{1},\mathbf {X} _{2},\ldots$ is required.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] where $x_{i}$ and $p_{i}$ are the i th component of the position and momentum vector respectively and H is the Hamiltonian.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] where $U(\mathbf {x} )$ is the potential energy.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] which comes from the Boltzmann's factor.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Note that the Hamiltonian H is dimensionless in this formulation because the exponential probability weight $\exp \left(-H\right)$ has to be well defined.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For example, in simulations at finite temperature T the factor $k_{\text{B}}T$ (with the Boltzmann constant $k_{\text{B}}$ ) is directly absorbed into U and M .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The algorithm requires a positive integer for number of leapfrog steps L and a positive number for the step size $\Delta t$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Suppose the chain is at $\mathbf {X} _{n}=\mathbf {x} _{n}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] First, a random Gaussian momentum $\mathbf {p} _{n}(0)$ is drawn from ${\text{N}}\left(\mathbf {0} ,M\right)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Next, the particle will run under Hamiltonian dynamics for time $L\Delta t$ , this is done by solving the Hamilton's equations numerically using the leapfrog algorithm.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] These equations are to be applied to $\mathbf {x} _{n}(0)$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}(0)$ L times to obtain $\mathbf {x} _{n}(L\Delta t)$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}(L\Delta t)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The leapfrog algorithm is an approximate solution to the motion of non-interacting classical particles.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] If exact, the solution will never change the initial randomly-generated energy distribution, as energy is conserved for each particle in the presence of a classical potential energy field.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] In order to reach a thermodynamic equilibrium distribution, particles must have some sort of interaction with, for example, a surrounding heat bath, so that the entire system can take on different energies with probabilities according to the Boltzmann distribution.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] One way to move the system towards a thermodynamic equilibrium distribution is to change the state of the particles using the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] So first, one applies the leapfrog step, then a Metropolis-Hastings step.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] A full update consists of first randomly sampling the momenta $\mathbf {p}$ (independently of the previous iterations), then integrating the equations of motion (e.g. with leapfrog), and finally obtaining the new configuration from the Metropolis-Hastings accept/reject step.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] This updating mechanism is repeated to obtain $\mathbf {X} _{n+1},\mathbf {X} _{n+2},\mathbf {X} _{n+3},\ldots$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The No U-Turn Sampler (NUTS) is an extension by controlling the number of steps L automatically.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For example, in the one dimensional ${\text{N}}(0,1/{\sqrt {k}})$ case, the potential is $U(x)=kx^{2}/2$ which corresponds to the potential of a simple harmonic oscillator.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For L too large, the particle will oscillate and thus waste computational time.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For L too small, the particle will behave like a random walk.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Loosely, NUTS runs the Hamiltonian dynamics both forwards and backwards in time randomly until a U-Turn condition is satisfied.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] When that happens, a random point from the path is chosen for the MCMC sample and the process is repeated from that new point.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] In detail, a binary tree is constructed to trace the path of the leap frog steps.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] To produce a MCMC sample, an iterative procedure is conducted.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Let $\mathbf {x} _{n}^{+}$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}^{+}$ be the position and momentum of the forward particle respectively.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] In each iteration, the binary tree selects at random uniformly to move the forward particle forwards in time or the backward particle backwards in time.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Also for each iteration, the number of leap frog steps increase by a factor of 2.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For example, in the first iteration, the forward particle moves forwards in time using 1 leap frog step.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] In the next iteration, the backward particle moves backwards in time using 2 leap frog steps.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] This is usually satisfied if the remaining HMC parameters are sensible.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] The method is known by different names in different disciplines.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] In particular, it is similar to the **velocity Verlet** method, which is a variant of Verlet integration.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] Leapfrog integration is equivalent to updating positions $x(t)$ and velocities $v(t)={\dot {x}}(t)$ at different interleaved time points, staggered in such a way that they "leapfrog" over each other.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] Leapfrog integration is a second-order method, in contrast to Euler integration, which is only first-order, yet requires the same number of function evaluations per step.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] Unlike Euler integration, it is stable for oscillatory motion, as long as the time-step $\Delta t$ is constant, and $\Delta t<2/\omega$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] Using Yoshida coefficients, applying the leapfrog integrator multiple times with the correct timesteps, a much higher order integrator can be generated.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] where $x_{i}$ is position at step i , $v_{i+1/2\,}$ is the velocity, or first derivative of x , at step $i+1/2\,$ , $a_{i}=A(x_{i})$ is the acceleration, or second derivative of x , at step i , and $\Delta t$ is the size of each time step.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] The separation of the acceleration calculation onto the beginning and end of a step means that if time resolution is increased by a factor of two ( $\Delta t\rightarrow \Delta t/2$ ), then only one extra (computationally expensive) acceleration calculation is required.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] One use of this equation is in Newtonian gravity simulations, since in that case the acceleration depends only on the positions of the gravitating masses (and not on their velocities).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] There are two primary strengths to leapfrog integration when applied to mechanics problems.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] The first is the time-reversibility of the Leapfrog method.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] One can integrate forward *n* steps, and then reverse the direction of integration and integrate backwards *n* steps to arrive at the same starting position.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] The second strength is its symplectic nature, which implies that it conserves the (slightly modified; see symplectic integrator) energy of a Hamiltonian dynamical system.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] This is especially useful when computing orbital dynamics, as many other integration schemes, such as the (order-4) Runge–Kutta method, do not conserve energy and allow the system to drift substantially over time.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] Because of its time-reversibility, and because it is a symplectic integrator, leapfrog integration is also used in Hamiltonian Monte Carlo, a method for drawing random samples from a probability distribution whose overall normalization is unknown.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] The leapfrog integrator can be converted into higher order integrators using techniques due to Haruo Yoshida.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] In this approach, the leapfrog is applied over a number of different timesteps.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] It turns out that when the correct timesteps are used in sequence, the errors cancel and far higher order integrators can be easily produced.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] One step under the 4th order Yoshida integrator requires four intermediary steps.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] The position and velocity are computed at different times.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] Only three (computationally expensive) acceleration calculations are required.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] All intermediary steps form one $\Delta t$ step which implies that coefficients sum up to one: ${\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{4}c_{i}=1}$ and ${\textstyle \sum _{i=1}^{3}d_{i}=1}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/leapfrog-integration] Note that position and velocity are computed at different times and some intermediary steps are backwards in time.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In statistics, **Markov chain Monte Carlo** (**MCMC**) is a class of algorithms used to draw samples from a probability distribution.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Given a probability distribution, one can construct a Markov chain whose elements' distribution approximates it, i.e. the Markov chain's equilibrium distribution matches the target distribution.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more steps that are included, the more closely the distribution of the sample matches the actual desired distribution.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are used to study probability distributions that are too complex or too high dimensional to study with analytic techniques alone.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Various algorithms exist for constructing such Markov chains, including the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods create samples from a continuous random variable, with probability density proportional to a known function.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These samples can be used to evaluate an integral over that variable, as its expected value or variance.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Practically, an ensemble of chains is generally developed, starting from a set of points arbitrarily chosen and sufficiently distant from each other.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These chains are stochastic processes of "walkers" which move around randomly according to an algorithm that looks for places with a reasonably high contribution to the integral to move into next, assigning them higher probabilities.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Random walk Monte Carlo methods are a kind of random simulation or Monte Carlo method.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, whereas the random samples of the integrand used in a conventional Monte Carlo integration are statistically independent, those used in MCMC are autocorrelated.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Correlations of samples introduces the need to use the Markov chain central limit theorem when estimating the error of mean values.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms create Markov chains such that they have an equilibrium distribution which is proportional to the function given.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The development of MCMC methods is deeply rooted in the early exploration of Monte Carlo (MC) techniques in the mid-20th century, particularly in physics.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These developments were marked by the Metropolis algorithm proposed by Nicholas Metropolis, Arianna W.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Rosenbluth, Marshall Rosenbluth, Augusta H.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Teller, and Edward Teller in 1953, which was designed to tackle high-dimensional integration problems using early computers.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Hastings generalized this algorithm and inadvertently introduced the component-wise updating idea, later known as Gibbs sampling.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Simultaneously, the theoretical foundations for Gibbs sampling were being developed, such as the Hammersley–Clifford theorem from Julian Besag's 1974 paper.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Although the seeds of MCMC were sown earlier, including the formal naming of Gibbs sampling in image processing by Stuart Geman and Donald Geman (1984) and the data augmentation method by Martin A.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This transformation was accompanied by significant theoretical advancements, such as Luke Tierney's (1994) rigorous treatment of MCMC convergence, and Jun S.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Liu, Wong, and Augustine Kong's (1994, 1995) analysis of Gibbs sampler structure.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Subsequent developments further expanded the MCMC toolkit, including particle filters (Sequential Monte Carlo) for sequential problems, Perfect sampling aiming for exact simulation (Jim Propp and David B.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Green, 1995) for handling variable-dimension models, and deeper investigations into convergence diagnostics and the central limit theorem.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overall, the evolution of MCMC represents a paradigm shift in statistical computation, enabling the analysis of numerous previously intractable complex models and continually expanding the scope and impact of statistics.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose *(Xn)* is a Markov Chain in the general state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ with specific properties.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Particularly, we hope to establish the Law of Large Numbers and the Central Limit Theorem for MCMC.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the following, we state some definitions and theorems necessary for the important convergence results.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In short, we need the existence of invariant measure and Harris recurrent to establish the Law of Large Numbers of MCMC (Ergodic Theorem).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] And we need aperiodicity, irreducibility and extra conditions such as reversibility to ensure the Central Limit Theorem holds in MCMC.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recall that in the discrete setting, a Markov chain is said to be *irreducible* if it is possible to reach any state from any other state in a finite number of steps with positive probability.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in the continuous setting, point-to-point transitions have zero probability.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, **φ-irreducibility** generalizes irreducibility by using a reference measure φ on the measurable space $({\mathcal {X}},{\mathcal {B}}({\mathcal {X}}))$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is a more general definition for irreducibility of a Markov chain in non-discrete state space.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the discrete case, an irreducible Markov chain is said to be *aperiodic* if it has period 1.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **Harris recurrent** if there exists a measure $\psi$ such that the chain is $\psi$ -irreducible and every measurable set A with $\psi (A)>0$ is Harris recurrent.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This definition is only needed when the state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ is uncountable.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the countable case, recurrence corresponds to $\mathbb {E} _{x}[\eta _{x}]=\infty$ , which is equivalent to $P_{x}(\tau _{x}<\infty )=1$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When there exists an *invariant probability measure* for a **ψ-irreducible** (hence recurrent) chain, the chain is said to be **positive recurrent**.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recurrent chains that do not allow for a finite invariant measure are called **null recurrent**.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In applications of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC), a very useful criterion for Harris recurrence involves the use of bounded harmonic functions.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These functions are *invariant* under the transition kernel in the functional sense, and they help characterize Harris recurrence.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This theorem provides a fundamental justification for the use of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods, and it serves as the counterpart of the Law of Large Numbers (LLN) in classical Monte Carlo.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] An important aspect of this result is that $\pi$ does not need to be a probability measure.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Therefore, there can be some type of strong stability even if the chain is null recurrent.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Moreover, the Markov chain can be started from arbitrary state.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is the Ergodic Theorem that we are more familiar with.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are several conditions under which the Central Limit Theorem (CLT) holds for Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One of the most commonly used is the condition of **reversibility**.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A stationary Markov chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **reversible** if the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n+2}=x$ is the same as the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n}=x$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] for every pair $(x,y)$ in the state space.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Even though reversibility is a restrictive assumption in theory, it is often easily satisfied in practical MCMC algorithms by introducing auxiliary variables or using symmetric proposal mechanisms.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are many other conditions that can be used to establish CLT for MCMC such as geometric ergodicity and the discrete state space.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods produce autocorrelated samples, in contrast to standard Monte Carlo techniques that draw independent samples.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Autocorrelation means successive draws from the Markov chain are statistically dependent, so each new sample adds less fresh information than an independent draw would.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As a result, one must account for this correlation when assessing the accuracy of estimates from the chain.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In particular, positive autocorrelation in the chain increases the variance of estimators and slows the convergence of sample averages toward the true expectation.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effect of correlation on estimation can be quantified through the Markov chain central limit theorem.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For a chain targeting a distribution with variance $\sigma ^{2}$ , the variance of the sample mean after N steps is approximately ${\sigma ^{2}}{\big /}N_{\text{eff}}$ , where $N_{\text{eff}}$ is an effective sample size smaller than N .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The term in parentheses, $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}$ , is often called the integrated autocorrelation.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When the chain has no autocorrelation ( $\rho _{k}=0$ for all $k\geq 1$ ), this factor equals 1, and one recovers the usual $\sigma ^{2}/N$ variance for independent samples.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the chain's samples are highly correlated, the sum of autocorrelations is large, leading to a much bigger variance for ${\bar {X}}_{N}$ than in the independent case.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effective sample size $N_{\text{eff}}$ is a useful diagnostic that translates the autocorrelation in a chain into an equivalent number of independent samples.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] so that $N_{\text{eff}}$ is the number of independent draws that would yield the same estimation precision as the N dependent draws from the Markov chain.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, if $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}=5$ , then $N_{\text{eff}}=N/5$ , meaning the chain of length N carries information equivalent to $N/5$ independent samples.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In an ideal scenario with no correlation, $\rho _{k}=0$ and thus $N_{\text{eff}}\approx N$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] But in a poorly mixing chain with strong autocorrelation, $N_{\text{eff}}$ can be much smaller than N .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, monitoring the ESS for each parameter is a way to gauge how much correlation is present: a low ESS indicates that many more iterations may be needed to achieve a desired effective sample of independent draws.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to address this problem could be shortening the steps of the walker, so that it does not continuously try to exit the highest probability region, though this way the process would be highly autocorrelated and expensive (i.e. many steps would be required for an accurate result).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] More sophisticated methods such as Hamiltonian Monte Carlo and the Wang and Landau algorithm use various ways of reducing this autocorrelation, while managing to keep the process in the regions that give a higher contribution to the integral.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms usually rely on a more complicated theory and are harder to implement, but they usually converge faster.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] We outline several general strategies such as reparameterization, adaptive proposal tuning, parameter blocking, and overrelaxation that help reduce correlation and improve sampling efficiency within the standard MCMC framework.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to reduce autocorrelation is to reformulate or reparameterize the statistical model so that the posterior geometry leads to more efficient sampling.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By changing the coordinate system or using alternative variable definitions, one can often lessen correlations.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, in Bayesian hierarchical modeling, a non-centered parameterization can be used in place of the standard (centered) formulation to avoid extreme posterior correlations between latent and higher-level parameters.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This involves expressing latent variables in terms of independent auxiliary variables, dramatically improving mixing.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Such reparameterization strategies are commonly employed in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithm to enhance convergence and reduce autocorrelation.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Another approach to reducing correlation is to improve the MCMC proposal mechanism.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, step size tuning is critical: if the proposed steps are too small, the sampler moves slowly and produces highly correlated samples; if the steps are too large, many proposals are rejected, resulting in repeated values.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adjusting the proposal step size during an initial testing phase helps find a balance where the sampler explores the space efficiently without too many rejections.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adaptive MCMC methods modify proposal distributions based on the chain's past samples.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, the adaptive Metropolis algorithm updates the Gaussian proposal distribution using the full information accumulated from the chain so far, allowing the proposal to adapt over time.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is a technique that reduces autocorrelation in MCMC by updating parameters jointly rather than one at a time.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When parameters exhibit strong posterior correlations, one-by-one updates can lead to poor mixing and slow exploration of the target distribution.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By identifying and sampling blocks of correlated parameters together, the sampler can more effectively traverse high-density regions of the posterior.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is commonly used in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithms.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In blocked Gibbs sampling, entire groups of variables are updated conditionally at each step.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings, multivariate proposals enable joint updates (i.e., updates of multiple parameters at once using a vector-valued proposal distribution, typically a multivariate Gaussian), though they often require careful tuning of the proposal covariance matrix.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is a technique to reduce autocorrelation between successive samples by proposing new samples that are negatively correlated with the current state.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This helps the chain explore the posterior more efficiently, especially in high-dimensional Gaussian models or when using Gibbs sampling.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The basic idea is to reflect the current sample across the conditional mean, producing proposals that retain the correct stationary distribution but with reduced serial dependence.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is particularly effective when combined with Gaussian conditional distributions, where exact reflection or partial overrelaxation can be analytically implemented.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting MCMC methodologies are a class of mean-field particle methods for obtaining random samples from a sequence of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In principle, any Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler can be turned into an interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers can be interpreted as a way to run in parallel a sequence of Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, interacting simulated annealing algorithms are based on independent Metropolis–Hastings moves interacting sequentially with a selection-resampling type mechanism.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In contrast to traditional Markov chain Monte Carlo methods, the precision parameter of this class of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers is *only* related to the number of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These advanced particle methodologies belong to the class of Feynman–Kac particle models, also called Sequential Monte Carlo or particle filter methods in Bayesian inference and signal processing communities.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mutation-selection genetic particle algorithm with Markov chain Monte Carlo mutations.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The quasi-Monte Carlo method is an analog to the normal Monte Carlo method that uses low-discrepancy sequences instead of random numbers.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] It yields an integration error that decays faster than that of true random sampling, as quantified by the Koksma–Hlawka inequality.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Empirically it allows the reduction of both estimation error and convergence time by an order of magnitude.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain quasi-Monte Carlo methods such as the Array–RQMC method combine randomized quasi–Monte Carlo and Markov chain simulation by simulating n chains simultaneously in a way that better approximates the true distribution of the chain than with ordinary MCMC.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In empirical experiments, the variance of the average of a function of the state sometimes converges at rate $O(n^{-2})$ or even faster, instead of the $O(n^{-1})$ Monte Carlo rate.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods are primarily used for calculating numerical approximations of multi-dimensional integrals, for example in Bayesian statistics, computational physics, computational biology and computational linguistics.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Bayesian statistics, Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are typically used to calculate moments and credible intervals of posterior probability distributions.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The use of MCMC methods makes it possible to compute large hierarchical models that require integrations over hundreds to thousands of unknown parameters.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Many contemporary research problems in statistical physics can be addressed by approximate solutions using Monte Carlo simulation, which provides valuable insights into the properties of complex systems.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Monte Carlo methods are fundamental in computational physics, astrophysics, physical chemistry, and related disciplines, with broad applications including medical physics, where they are employed to model radiation transport for radiation dosimetry calculations.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead of exhaustively analyzing all possible system states, the Monte Carlo method randomly examines a subset of them to form a representative sample, and yields accurate approximations of the system's characteristic properties.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As the number of sampled states increases, the error can be further reduced to a lower level.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Langevin Dynamics are typically used in complex distribution sampling and generative modeling, via an MCMC procedure.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Specifically, given the probability density function $p(x)$ , we use its log gradient $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ as the score function and start from a prior distribution $x_{0}\sim p_{0}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When $\epsilon \rightarrow 0$ and $K\rightarrow \infty$ , $x_{K}$ converges to a sample from the target distribution $p(x)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For some complex distribution, if we know its probability density function but find it difficult to directly sample from it, we can apply Langevin Dynamics as an alternate.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in most cases, especially generative modeling, usually we do not know the exact probability density function of the target distribution we wish to sample from, neither the score function $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, score matching methods provide feasible solutions, minimizing the Fisher information metric between a parameterized score-based model $s_{\theta }(x)$ and the score function without knowing the ground-truth data score.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The score function can be estimated on a training dataset by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In real cases, however, the training data only takes a small region of the target distribution, and the estimated score functions are inaccurate in other low density regions with fewer available data examples.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] To overcome this challenge, denoising score matching methods perturb the available data examples with noise of different scales, which can improve the coverage of low density regions, and use them as the training dataset for the score-base model.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Note that the choice of noise scales is tricky, as too large noise will corrupt the original data, while too small noise will not populate the original data to those low density regions.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Thus, carefully crafted noise schedules are applied for higher quality generation.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Usually it is not hard to construct a Markov chain with the desired properties.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more difficult problem is to determine (1) when to start collecting statistics and (2) how many steps are needed to converge to the stationary distribution within an acceptable error.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Fortunately, there are a variety of practical diagnostics to empirically assess convergence.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Formally, let $\pi$ denote the stationary distribution and $P^{t}(x,\cdot )$ the distribution of the Markov chain after t steps starting from state x .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A chain is said to mix rapidly if $d_{\text{TV}}(P^{t}(x,\cdot ),\pi )\leq \epsilon$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ within a small number of steps t under a pre-defined tolerance $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In other words, the stationary distribution is reached quickly starting from an arbitrary position, and the minimum such t is known as the mixing time.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, however, the total variation distance is generally intractable to compute, especially in high-dimensional problems or when the stationary distribution is only known up to a normalizing constant (as in most Bayesian applications).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Gelman-Rubin statistic, also known as the **potential scale reduction factor (PSRF)**, evaluates MCMC convergence by sampling multiple independent Markov chains and comparing within-chain and between-chain variances.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If all chains have converged to the same stationary distribution, the between-chain and within-chain variances should be similar, and thus the PSRF must approach 1.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, a value of $<1.1$ is often taken as evidence of convergence.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Higher values suggest that the chains are still exploring different parts of the target distribution.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Geweke diagnostic examines whether the distribution of samples in the early part of the Markov chain is statistically indistinguishable from the distribution in a later part.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Since MCMC samples are autocorrelated, a simple comparison of sample means is insufficient.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead, the difference in means is standardized using an estimator of the spectral density at zero frequency, which accounts for the long-range dependencies in the chain.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the long-run variance (i.e., the spectral density at frequency zero), commonly estimated using Newey-West estimators or batch means.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the statistic Z follows an approximately standard normal distribution $Z\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If $|Z|>1.96$ , the null hypothesis is rejected at the 5% significance level, suggesting that the chain has not yet reached stationarity.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Heidelberger-Welch diagnostic is grounded in spectral analysis and Brownian motion theory, and is particularly useful in the early stages of simulation to determine appropriate burn-in and stopping time.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The diagnostic consists of two components, a **stationarity test** that assesses whether the Markov chain has reached a steady-state, and a **half-width test** that determines whether the estimated expectation is within a user-specified precision.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let $\{X_{t}\}_{t=1}^{n}$ be the output of an MCMC simulation for a scalar function $g(X_{t})$ , and $g_{1},g_{2},\dots ,g_{n}$ the evaluations of the function g over the chain.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\bar {g}}_{n}={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}g_{i}$ is the sample mean and ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the spectral density at frequency zero.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the process $B_{n}(t)$ converges in distribution to a Brownian bridge.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This statistic is compared against known critical values from the Brownian bridge distribution.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the null hypothesis is rejected, the first 10% of the samples are discarded and the test can be repeated on the remaining chain until either stationarity is accepted or 50% of the chain is discarded.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Once stationarity is accepted, the second part of the diagnostic checks whether the Monte Carlo estimator is accurate enough for practical use.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ is an estimate of the variance of $g(X)$ , $t_{\alpha /2,\nu }$ is the Student's t critical value at confidence level $1-\alpha$ and degrees of freedom $\nu$ , n is the number of samples used.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the half-width is smaller than a user-defined tolerance (e.g., 0.05), the chain is considered long enough to estimate the expectation reliably.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Otherwise, the simulation should be extended.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is specifically designed to assess how many iterations are needed to estimate quantiles or tail probabilities of the target distribution with a desired accuracy and confidence.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Unlike Gelman-Rubin or Geweke diagnostics, which are based on assessing convergence to the entire distribution, the Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is goal-oriented as it provides estimates for the number of samples required to estimate a specific quantile of interest within a desired margin of error.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let q denote the desired quantile (e.g., 0.025) of a real-valued function $g(X)$ : in other words, the goal is to find u such that $P(g(X)\leq u)=q$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose we wish to estimate this quantile such that the estimate falls within margin $\varepsilon$ of the true value with probability $1-\alpha$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $I(\cdot )$ is the indicator function.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The sequence $\{W_{n}\}$ is treated as a realization from a two-state Markov chain.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] While this may not be strictly true, it is often a good approximation in practice.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $\Phi ^{-1}(\cdot )$ is the standard normal quantile function.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In statistics and statistical physics, the **Metropolis–Hastings algorithm** is a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) method for obtaining a sequence of random samples from a probability distribution from which direct sampling is difficult.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] New samples are added to the sequence in two steps: first a new sample is proposed based on the previous sample, then the proposed sample is either added to the sequence or rejected depending on the value of the probability distribution at that point.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The resulting sequence can be used to approximate the distribution (e.g. to generate a histogram) or to compute an integral (e.g. an expected value).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Metropolis–Hastings and other MCMC algorithms are generally used for sampling from multi-dimensional distributions, especially when the number of dimensions is high.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For single-dimensional distributions, there are usually other methods (e.g. adaptive rejection sampling) that can directly return independent samples from the distribution, and these are free from the problem of autocorrelated samples that is inherent in MCMC methods.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The algorithm is named in part for Nicholas Metropolis, the first coauthor of a 1953 paper, entitled *Equation of State Calculations by Fast Computing Machines*, with Arianna W.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For many years the algorithm was known simply as the *Metropolis algorithm*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The paper proposed the algorithm for the case of symmetrical proposal distributions, but in 1970, W.K.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Hastings extended it to the more general case.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The generalized method was eventually identified by both names, although the first use of the term "Metropolis-Hastings algorithm" is unclear.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Some controversy exists with regard to credit for development of the Metropolis algorithm.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Metropolis, who was familiar with the computational aspects of the method, had coined the term "Monte Carlo" in an earlier article with Stanisław Ulam, and led the group in the Theoretical Division that designed and built the MANIAC I computer used in the experiments in 1952.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] However, prior to 2003 there was no detailed account of the algorithm's development.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Shortly before his death, Marshall Rosenbluth attended a 2003 conference at LANL marking the 50th anniversary of the 1953 publication.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] At this conference, Rosenbluth described the algorithm and its development in a presentation titled "Genesis of the Monte Carlo Algorithm for Statistical Mechanics".
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Further historical clarification is made by Gubernatis in a 2005 journal article recounting the 50th anniversary conference.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Rosenbluth makes it clear that he and his wife Arianna did the work, and that Metropolis played no role in the development other than providing computer time.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This contradicts an account by Edward Teller, who states in his memoirs that the five authors of the 1953 article worked together for "days (and nights)".
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In contrast, the detailed account by Rosenbluth credits Teller with a crucial but early suggestion to "take advantage of statistical mechanics and take ensemble averages instead of following detailed kinematics".
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This, says Rosenbluth, started him thinking about the generalized Monte Carlo approach – a topic which he says he had discussed often with John Von Neumann.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Arianna Rosenbluth recounted (to Gubernatis in 2003) that Augusta Teller started the computer work, but that Arianna herself took it over and wrote the code from scratch.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In an oral history recorded shortly before his death, Rosenbluth again credits Teller with posing the original problem, himself with solving it, and Arianna with programming the computer.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm can draw samples from any probability distribution with probability density $P(x)$ , provided that we know a function $f(x)$ proportional to the density P and the values of $f(x)$ can be calculated.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The requirement that $f(x)$ must only be proportional to the density, rather than exactly equal to it, makes the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm particularly useful, because it removes the need to calculate the density's normalization factor, which is often extremely difficult in practice.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm generates a sequence of sample values in such a way that, as more and more sample values are produced, the distribution of values more closely approximates the desired distribution.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] These sample values are produced iteratively in such a way, that the distribution of the next sample depends only on the current sample value, which makes the sequence of samples a Markov chain.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Specifically, at each iteration, the algorithm proposes a candidate for the next sample value based on the current sample value.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Then, with some probability, the candidate is either accepted, in which case the candidate value is used in the next iteration, or it is rejected in which case the candidate value is discarded, and the current value is reused in the next iteration.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The probability of acceptance is determined by comparing the values of the function $f(x)$ of the current and candidate sample values with respect to the desired distribution.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The method used to propose new candidates is characterized by the probability distribution $g(x\mid y)$ (sometimes written $Q(x\mid y)$ ) of a new proposed sample x given the previous sample y .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is called the *proposal density*, *proposal function*, or *jumping distribution*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] A common choice for $g(x\mid y)$ is a Gaussian distribution centered at y , so that points closer to y are more likely to be visited next, making the sequence of samples into a Gaussian random walk.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In the original paper by Metropolis et al.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] (1953), $g(x\mid y)$ was suggested to be a uniform distribution limited to some maximum distance from y .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] More complicated proposal functions are also possible, such as those of Hamiltonian Monte Carlo, Langevin Monte Carlo, or preconditioned Crank–Nicolson.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For the purpose of illustration, the Metropolis algorithm, a special case of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm where the proposal function is symmetric, is described below.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Let $f(x)$ be a function that is proportional to the desired probability density function $P(x)$ (a.k.a. a target distribution).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This algorithm proceeds by randomly attempting to move about the sample space, sometimes accepting the moves and sometimes remaining in place. $P(x)$ at specific point x is proportional to the iterations spent on the point by the algorithm.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Note that the acceptance ratio $\alpha$ indicates how probable the new proposed sample is with respect to the current sample, according to the distribution whose density is $P(x)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] If we attempt to move to a point that is more probable than the existing point (i.e. a point in a higher-density region of $P(x)$ corresponding to an $\alpha >1\geq u$ ), we will always accept the move.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] However, if we attempt to move to a less probable point, we will sometimes reject the move, and the larger the relative drop in probability, the more likely we are to reject the new point.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Thus, we will tend to stay in (and return large numbers of samples from) high-density regions of $P(x)$ , while only occasionally visiting low-density regions.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Intuitively, this is why this algorithm works and returns samples that follow the desired distribution with density $P(x)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] On the other hand, most simple rejection sampling methods suffer from the "curse of dimensionality", where the probability of rejection increases exponentially as a function of the number of dimensions.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Metropolis–Hastings, along with other MCMC methods, do not have this problem to such a degree, and thus are often the only solutions available when the number of dimensions of the distribution to be sampled is high.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] As a result, MCMC methods are often the methods of choice for producing samples from hierarchical Bayesian models and other high-dimensional statistical models used nowadays in many disciplines.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In multivariate distributions, the classic Metropolis–Hastings algorithm as described above involves choosing a new multi-dimensional sample point.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] When the number of dimensions is high, finding the suitable jumping distribution to use can be difficult, as the different individual dimensions behave in very different ways, and the jumping width (see above) must be "just right" for all dimensions at once to avoid excessively slow mixing.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] An alternative approach that often works better in such situations, known as Gibbs sampling, involves choosing a new sample for each dimension separately from the others, rather than choosing a sample for all dimensions at once.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] That way, the problem of sampling from potentially high-dimensional space will be reduced to a collection of problems to sample from small dimensionality.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is especially applicable when the multivariate distribution is composed of a set of individual random variables in which each variable is conditioned on only a small number of other variables, as is the case in most typical hierarchical models.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The individual variables are then sampled one at a time, with each variable conditioned on the most recent values of all the others.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The purpose of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm is to generate a collection of states according to a desired distribution $P(x)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] To accomplish this, the algorithm uses a Markov process, which asymptotically reaches a unique stationary distribution $\pi (x)$ such that $\pi (x)=P(x)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] A Markov process is uniquely defined by its transition probabilities $P(x'\mid x)$ , the probability of transitioning from any given state x to any other given state $x'$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] *Uniqueness of stationary distribution*: the stationary distribution $\pi (x)$ must be unique.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is guaranteed by ergodicity of the Markov process, which requires that every state must (1) be aperiodic—the system does not return to the same state at fixed intervals; and (2) be positive recurrent—the expected number of steps for returning to the same state is finite.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm involves designing a Markov process (by constructing transition probabilities) that fulfills the two above conditions, such that its stationary distribution $\pi (x)$ is chosen to be $P(x)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The approach is to separate the transition in two sub-steps; the proposal and the acceptance-rejection.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The proposal distribution $g(x'\mid x)$ is the conditional probability of proposing a state $x'$ given x , and the acceptance distribution $A(x',x)$ is the probability to accept the proposed state $x'$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The next step in the derivation is to choose an acceptance ratio that fulfills the condition above.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For this Metropolis acceptance ratio A , either $A(x',x)=1$ or $A(x,x')=1$ and, either way, the condition is satisfied.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] 3. if $u>A(x',x_{t})$ , then *reject* the new state, and copy the old state forward $x_{t+1}=x_{t}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Provided that specified conditions are met, the empirical distribution of saved states $x_{0},\ldots ,x_{T}$ will approach $P(x)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The number of iterations ( T ) required to effectively estimate $P(x)$ depends on the number of factors, including the relationship between $P(x)$ and the proposal distribution and the desired accuracy of estimation.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For distribution on discrete state spaces, it has to be of the order of the autocorrelation time of the Markov process.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] An accessible account of the convergence theory for Metropolis–Hastings is given in.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] It is important to notice that it is not clear, in a general problem, which distribution $g(x'\mid x)$ one should use or the number of iterations necessary for proper estimation; both are free parameters of the method, which must be adjusted to the particular problem in hand.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] A common use of Metropolis–Hastings algorithm is to compute an integral.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Specifically, consider a space $\Omega \subset \mathbb {R}$ and a probability distribution $P(x)$ over $\Omega$ , $x\in \Omega$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] where $A(x)$ is a (measurable) function of interest.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For example, consider a statistic $E(x)$ and its probability distribution $P(E)$ , which is a marginal distribution.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Suppose that the goal is to estimate $P(E)$ for E on the tail of $P(E)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] and, thus, estimating $P(E)$ can be accomplished by estimating the expected value of the indicator function $A_{E}(x)\equiv \mathbf {1} _{E}(x)$ , which is 1 when $E(x)\in [E,E+\Delta E]$ and zero otherwise.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Because E is on the tail of $P(E)$ , the probability to draw a state x with $E(x)$ on the tail of $P(E)$ is proportional to $P(E)$ , which is small by definition.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm can be used here to sample (rare) states more likely and thus increase the number of samples used to estimate $P(E)$ on the tails.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This can be done e.g. by using a sampling distribution $\pi (x)$ to favor those states (e.g. $\pi (x)\propto e^{aE}$ with $a>0$ ).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Suppose that the most recent value sampled is $x_{t}$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] is the ratio of the proposal density in two directions (from $x_{t}$ to $x'$ and conversely).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is equal to 1 if the proposal density is symmetric.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Then the new state $x_{t+1}$ is chosen according to the following rules.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Markov chain is started from an arbitrary initial value $x_{0}$ , and the algorithm is run for many iterations until this initial state is "forgotten".
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] These samples, which are discarded, are known as *burn-in*.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The remaining set of accepted values of x represent a sample from the distribution $P(x)$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The algorithm works best if the proposal density matches the shape of the target distribution $P(x)$ , from which direct sampling is difficult, that is $g(x'\mid x_{t})\approx P(x')$ .
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] If a Gaussian proposal density g is used, the variance parameter $\sigma ^{2}$ has to be tuned during the burn-in period.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is usually done by calculating the *acceptance rate*, which is the fraction of proposed samples that is accepted in a window of the last N samples.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The desired acceptance rate depends on the target distribution, however it has been shown theoretically that the ideal acceptance rate for a one-dimensional Gaussian distribution is about 50%, decreasing to about 23% for an N -dimensional Gaussian target distribution.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] These guidelines can work well when sampling from sufficiently regular Bayesian posteriors as they often follow a multivariate normal distribution as can be established using the Bernstein–von Mises theorem.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] If $\sigma ^{2}$ is too small, the chain will *mix slowly* (i.e., the acceptance rate will be high, but successive samples will move around the space slowly, and the chain will converge only slowly to $P(x)$ ).
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] On the other hand, if $\sigma ^{2}$ is too large, the acceptance rate will be very low because the proposals are likely to land in regions of much lower probability density, so $a_{1}$ will be very small, and again the chain will converge very slowly.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] One typically tunes the proposal distribution so that the algorithms accepts on the order of 30% of all samples – in line with the theoretical estimates mentioned in the previous paragraph.
[src:hamiltonian-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] MCMC can be used to draw samples from the posterior distribution of a statistical model.
